University of Michigan's
Center for Information Technology Integration (CITI)
Presents a Non-Credit Course on:
The Open Software Foundation's (OSF)

Distributed Computing Environment Features and Functionality
September 14, 1994


The "Distributed Computing Environment (DCE) Features and
Functionality" course provides an architectural overview of the OSF's DCE
and its component services. It illustrates how DCE services interoperate
and
depend on one another to create a distributed environment over a variety
of
platforms.

Topics Featured:

* DCE Architecture		* Distributed Time Service
* Threads			* Security
* Remote Procedure Calls	* Distributed File Service
* Directory Service		* Diskless Support Service

A familiarity with distributed system concepts and programming experience
is recommended.

Instructor:  Charles J. Antonelli, Ph.D., Computer, Information, and
Control Engineering
for Research in Exception Handling in Parallel Environments, is an
assistant research
scientist at CITI. and adjunct assistant professor in the Electrical
Engineering and
Computer Science Department at the University of Michigan. He is active
in IEEE Storage
Systems Standards Working Group and maintains contact with the Ada
community through
participation in Real-Time Ada workshops.

